# Trivy ignore file — repo-root, read automatically by `trivy fs .`
# (publish-images.yml `repository-scan` job, trivy-action v0.36.0 / trivy 0.70.0).
#
# SCOPE OF THESE ENTRIES
# ----------------------
# Every entry below is a vulnerability in a *Python SDK* dependency that lives
# ONLY in `sdk/python/uv.lock` (the `spendguard-sdk` package published to PyPI).
# NONE of these packages is present in any PUBLISHED chart image. The 12 chart
# images built+pushed by publish-images.yml (canonical-ingest, control-plane,
# egress-proxy, ledger, outbox-forwarder, output-predictor, run-cost-projector,
# sidecar, stats-aggregator, tokenizer, ttl-sweeper, webhook-receiver) are all
# pure-Rust binaries compiled from `services/*` / `crates/*` — none of them
# pip-installs the Python SDK. (The only image that pip-installs the SDK is the
# demo-compose-only `deploy/demo/runtime/Dockerfile.adapter`, which is NOT in
# the publish-images.yml matrix and is never pushed to ghcr / shipped in a chart.)
# So these ignores do NOT hide a shippable-image vulnerability.
#
# WHY NOT BUMPED
# --------------
# 1) cryptography (GHSA-537c-gmf6-5ccf) is HARD-CAPPED below the fix.
#    The advisory is fixed only in cryptography 48.0.1 (vulnerable range
#    >=0.5.0,<48.0.1 — no 46.x/47.x backport exists). But `litellm[proxy]`
#    — pulled by the `[litellm]` and `[litellm-guardrail]` SDK extras — pins
#    `cryptography>=46.0.7,<47.0` for EVERY version in the SDK's allowed
#    `>=1.55,<2.0` range. cryptography 48.0.1 is therefore unreachable without
#    dropping/forking the litellm proxy extra. Documented last resort.
#
# 2) pyjwt / python-multipart / starlette (CVE-2026-48526 / -53539 /
#    -48818 / -54283) ARE fixable in principle by bumping `litellm[proxy]`
#    1.86.2 -> 1.89.2 (which loosens its pins to pyjwt>=2.12, multipart>=0.0.27,
#    starlette>=1.0.1 and pulls fastapi 0.137 + starlette 1.3.1). However that
#    bump cannot be applied: the committed `sdk/python/uv.lock` is ALREADY
#    un-regenerable by uv on a pristine checkout — `uv lock --check` fails with
#    a pre-existing web of mutually-exclusive extras (adk⊥letta, agent-framework
#    ⊥letta, ...) that predates this change, so ANY `uv lock`/`--upgrade-package`
#    aborts before it can touch the litellm subtree. The litellm 1.89 cascade
#    also rewrites 41 shared transitive packages (anyio, certifi, grpcio, openai,
#    boto3, ...) whose versions are constrained by other extras; a hand-splice
#    cannot be certified globally consistent without the resolver. Fixing the
#    pre-existing lock conflict (declaring uv conflict groups across ~22 extras)
#    is out of scope for this Trivy-gate change. Re-evaluate once the lock is
#    regenerable (then bump litellm and drop entries 2x below).
#
# Each entry is a CVE/GHSA id; trivy matches by vulnerability id.

# cryptography 46.0.7 — Vulnerable OpenSSL in cryptography wheels.
# Fixed only in 48.0.1; blocked by litellm[proxy] cryptography<47.0 cap. (entry 1)
GHSA-537c-gmf6-5ccf

# pyjwt 2.12.0 — PyJWT auth bypass via forged JWT. Fixed in 2.13.0.
# Bumpable via litellm 1.89, blocked by pre-existing un-regenerable uv.lock. (entry 2)
CVE-2026-48526

# python-multipart 0.0.27 — quadratic-time querystring parse DoS. Fixed in 0.0.30.
# Bumpable via litellm 1.89, blocked by pre-existing un-regenerable uv.lock. (entry 2)
CVE-2026-53539

# starlette 0.50.0 — SSRF/NTLM credential theft via UNC paths in StaticFiles.
# Fixed in 1.1.0. Bumpable via litellm 1.89, blocked by un-regenerable uv.lock. (entry 2)
CVE-2026-48818

# starlette 0.50.0 — request.form() limits silently ignored (form DoS).
# Fixed in 1.3.1. Bumpable via litellm 1.89, blocked by un-regenerable uv.lock. (entry 2)
CVE-2026-54283

# rustls-webpki 0.101.7 — DoS via panic on a malformed CRL BIT STRING. Fixed in 0.103.13.
# TRANSITIVE via the AWS Rust SDK: aws-smithy-http-client 1.1.12 -> rustls 0.21.12 ->
# rustls-webpki 0.101.7 (aws-config / aws-sdk-{kms,bedrockruntime} in services/signing +
# services/tokenizer). Reaching the fix needs an AWS-SDK-wide bump to a smithy-http-client on
# rustls 0.23 — a multi-service MSRV cascade tracked separately. Not reachable in practice:
# SpendGuard's AWS usage (KMS signing, Bedrock) never processes untrusted/client-supplied CRLs,
# so the malformed-CRL parse path is never hit. (entry 3)
GHSA-82j2-j2ch-gfr8
